I had to use this feature for receipt-like printing recently. Here is the snippet that I used (with hardcoded width from my printer):

```python
def leftright(p, left, right, font='b'):
    if font == 'a':
        p.textln("{:<20}{:>12}".format(left, right))
    else:
        p.textln("{:<30}{:>12}".format(left, right))
```

Maybe we can think of a kind of API for this. At least it will help if someone wants to do this right now without using a cleaner solution (I think this is Python 3 only).

@pde should also chime in on this as he's likely to have an opinion, but what about solution similar to what we use for [enabling backports on Debian](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/blob/master/letsencrypt-auto-source/pieces/bootstrappers/deb_common.sh#L49) or [enabling EPEL on CentOS](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/blob/master/letsencrypt-auto-source/pieces/bootstrappers/rpm_common.sh#L38)? Unfortunately, to many people's frustration, when we first wrote `letsencrypt-auto`, it never prompted the user before calling `letsencrypt/certbot` (see #2229). We've fixed this in `certbot-auto`, however, we've preserved this behavior in `letsencrypt-auto` because it is what people are used to and they have built integrations around it.

In the current `*-auto` scripts, the environment variable `$ASSUME_YES` is set to 1 if the user provides `-n/--noninteractive/--non-interactive` on the command line or the name of the script is `letsencrypt-auto`. We can use this variable to do something similar for `mod_ssl`. If `$ASSUME_YES` is 1, we install `mod_ssl` without prompting the user. If it isn't, we prompt the user explaining that `mod_ssl` is needed to use the Apache plugin and ask for permission to install it.

I don't have a strong preference whether we ask the question using `read` and then provide `-y` to `yum/dnf` or simply provide more context and allow `yum/dnf` to ask the question like we do for EPEL on CentOS. Additionally, we should make sure the Apache plugin fails somewhat gracefully when `mod_ssl` isn't installed.

